oh! I just got oriented to what's happening here, and there's a much more elegant approach that gets rid of the race between `getPod` and `Update` entirely

Update already gets from etcd internally, then hands a copy of the old pod to the UpdatedObjectInfo getter and passes it through the transformer chain

Rather than plumbing `pod` to addConditionAndDeletePod`, update our transformer chain to transform the pod coming from etcd, adding in the resourceVersion and UID precondition if applicable, along with our conditions:

```go
setPreconditions := func(_ context.Context, _, oldObj runtime.Object) (runtime.Object, error) {
  oldPodCopy := oldObj.(*api.Pod).DeepCopy()
  if options.Preconditions != nil {
    if uid := options.Preconditions.UID; uid != nil && len(*uid) > 0 {
      oldPodCopy.UID = *uid
    }
    if rv := options.Preconditions.ResourceVersion; rv != nil && len(*rv) > 0 {
      oldPodCopy.ResourceVersion = *rv
    }
  }
  return oldPodCopy, nil
}
conditionAppender := ...
conditionedPod := rest.DefaultUpdatedObjectInfo(nil, setPreconditions, conditionAppender)
```

if the precondition uid or resourceVersion conflicts with what's already in etcd, Update will return a conflict appropriately

if there was no precondition uid or resourceVersion, Update will handle retrying internally as needed

then continue with what you have here, updating the resourceVersion in `options` with the resulting resourceVersion from our Update call

