Oh, this feature gate doesn't belong in generic k8s.io/apiserver features, it's specific to kubernetes components. Move this to pkg/features/kube_features.go

That's going to make plumbing difficult :-/

I'm remembering more about this now... we explicitly didn't want the meaning of PSS policies to be stateful or vary between clusters or rely on feature toggles.

A hacky way to make the kube-apiserver-constructed admission instance be informed by kube-apiserver-specific gates is to do something like this:

In staging/src/k8s.io/pod-security-admission/policy/helpers.go:
```go
var relaxPolicyForUserNamespacePods = &atomic.Bool{}

// RelaxPolicyForUserNamespacePods allows opting into relaxing runAsUser / runAsNonRoot restricted policies for user namespace pods,
// before the usernamespace feature has reached GA and propagated to the oldest supported nodes.
// This should only be opted into in clusters where the administrator ensures all nodes in the cluster enable the user namespace feature.
func RelaxPolicyForUserNamespacePods(relax bool) {
  relaxPolicyForUserNamespacePods.Store(relax)
} 

func relaxPolicyForUserNamespacePod(podSpec *corev1.PodSpec) bool {
	return relaxPolicyForUserNamespacePods.Load() && podSpec != nil && podSpec.HostUsers != nil && !*podSpec.HostUsers
}
```

In plugin/pkg/admission/security/podsecurity.Plugin#InspectFeatureGates:
```go
policy.RelaxPolicyForUserNamespacePods(featureGates.Enabled(features.UserNamespacesPodSecurityStandards))
```

